<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920123-0045</DOCNO><DOCID>920123-0045.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Neiman Marcus Group Inc.:   Sales Outlook Is Cautious   For First Half of This Year</HL><DATE>01/23/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   NMG</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)</IN><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Neiman Marcus Group Inc., emerging from a lacklusterChristmas selling season, said its sales outlook remainsguarded at least for the first half of 1992.   Robert J. Tarr Jr., president and chief executive officer,said at the company's annual meeting that same-store salesfor its 1991 holiday season, from Nov. 29 through Dec. 24,fell 2.6% compared with a year earlier. Same-store sales aresales in stores open at least one year. The sales declinecame despite a &quot;soft 1990&quot; holiday selling season, Mr. Tarradded.</LP><TEXT>   Unlike other recessions, Mr. Tarr noted, this downturn hasstruck the white-collar and professional ranks, whichconstitute the retailer's core customers at its Neiman Marcusand Bergdorf Goodman stores. Neiman Marcus, based in Newton,Mass., also operates Contempo Casuals, a retail chain thatcaters to younger shoppers.   The soft retail environment, now entering its fourth year,is expected to continue through the spring, he added. As aresult, Mr. Tarr characterized as &quot;cautious&quot; the company'soutlook for its spring selling season, from February to July.The projected recessionary market would affect the company'sfiscal third quarter ending May 4 and fourth quarter endingAug. 3, a company spokesman added.   However, industry projections call for an improvement inthe retail business beginning in September, and the company,which has remodeled many of its stores, ought to bewell-positioned to gain from such a turn in the economy, saidMr. Tarr.</TEXT></DOC>